<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Lesson 07 ‚Äî Formatted Strings</h1>
        
        <h2><strong>Assignment Instructions</strong></h2>
        <p>For this activity, you will:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>Open a new notebook in <strong>Google Colab</strong> and give it a title that reflects <strong>Lesson 07 ‚Äî Formatted Strings</strong>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Create variables for a player's information (name, team, points, rebounds, assists) and use an <strong>f-string</strong> to display them in a formatted sentence (e.g., <code>f"{player} scored {points} points for the {team}."</code>).</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Practice <strong>concatenation</strong> by combining strings with the <code>+</code> operator to build a full sentence from multiple variables, then compare it to using an f-string for the same output.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Use f-strings to create a <strong>player stat card</strong> that displays multiple statistics in an organized format with labels (e.g., "Name: Stephen Curry | Team: Warriors | PPG: 30.1").</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Embed <strong>expressions</strong> inside f-strings by performing calculations directly within the curly braces (e.g., <code>f"Field Goal Percentage: {made / attempts * 100:.1f}%"</code>).</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Use f-string <strong>formatting options</strong> to control decimal places for floating-point numbers (e.g., <code>{value:.2f}</code> for 2 decimal places).</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Create a sports report template using a multi-line f-string with triple quotes that incorporates multiple variables and calculations.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>Save and submit your completed notebook through <strong>Google Classroom</strong> when finished.</p>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <div class="note">
            <strong>üí° F-String Tips:</strong>
            <ul style="margin: 10px 0;">
                <li>Always start with <code>f</code> before the opening quote: <code>f"..."</code></li>
                <li>Put variables and expressions inside curly braces: <code>{variable}</code></li>
                <li>Format numbers with <code>:.2f</code> for 2 decimals, <code>:.1f</code> for 1 decimal</li>
                <li>You can do math inside the braces: <code>{points + rebounds + assists}</code></li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="note">
